' Generated by scripts/service.mjs - do not edit by hand.
'
' Launches Project Minder's server with no visible console window (Task
' Scheduler's action is wscript.exe running THIS file, rather than node.exe
' or cmd.exe directly, which would otherwise flash a console window on every
' logon). Also sets PORT/HOSTNAME so the standalone server binds where the
' dashboard expects it (scripts/package-standalone.mjs's server.js wrapper
' reads these from the environment; the "next start" fallback ignores them
' and uses its own -p flag instead, so setting them unconditionally is safe
' either way).
'
' PATH (F15 review fix — Windows side of it): deliberately NOT overridden
' here, unlike the macOS plist/Linux systemd unit. A Scheduled Task
' registered with LogonType=InteractiveToken (this task's Principal, see
' windows-task.xml.tmpl) runs with the SAME environment block an ordinary
' interactive logon gets, including PATH as stored in the user/machine
' registry environment (HKCU/HKLM \Environment) — which is exactly where
' installers (git, gh, nvm-windows, etc.) register themselves. This is a
' documented Windows Task Scheduler behavior, unlike launchd/systemd user
' services, which run in a minimal, non-login environment. Freezing an
' install-time PATH copy here would actually be WORSE than the current
' behavior: it would stop tracking PATH changes the live registry already
' reflects on every future run. If a future finding shows this assumption
' doesn't hold in practice, add a WshEnv("PATH") line mirroring the
' plist/unit's install-time capture.
Set WshShell = CreateObject("WScript.Shell")
WshShell.CurrentDirectory = "{{WORKING_DIR}}"
Set WshEnv = WshShell.Environment("PROCESS")
WshEnv("PORT") = "{{PORT}}"
WshEnv("HOSTNAME") = "{{HOSTNAME}}"
WshShell.Run "{{COMMAND_LINE}}", 0, False
